Set ARCOS R Package API Key

For this exercise, we will be working with subsets of the DEA’s ARCOS database, which documented shipments of 76 billion opioid pills between 2006 and 2014, during the peak of the opioid epidemic.

The data was obtained after a lengthy legal battle by the Washington Post and the Charleston Gazette-Mail, and released by the Washington Post in raw and aggregated form. Washington Post “Digging into the DEA’s pain pill database” page.

A data dictionary is available here: ARCOS Registrant Handbook.

We’re going to load opioid data exclusively from the arcos R package API ARCOS API produced by the Washington Post, instead of uploading csvs and tsvs.

Remember, we need to store a password of sorts – called an API key – that will give us permission to access their data. Here’s a list of API keys that will work.

Store the key first.

# store the ARCOS API key as an object called key
key <- "uO4EK6I"

Load Data

Load the data you’ll need for this assignment.

We’ll need two tables.

The first: a table with the total number of pills sent to each U.S. county in each year from 2006 to 2014 . We’ll use the summarized_county_annual() function from the ARCOS API package.

arcos_county_pills_per_year <- summarized_county_annual(key = key) %>%
  as_data_frame() %>%
  clean_names()

# Step 3: Join together table with pills by county by year with table with population by county by year
pills_population <- arcos_county_population_per_year %>%
  left_join(arcos_county_pills_per_year, by = c("countyfips", "year", "buyer_county","buyer_state"))

# Step 4: Filter the pills population table just for West Virginia and create the pills per person metric.  

pills_population_county_wv <- pills_population %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV") %>%
  group_by(countyfips, buyer_county, buyer_state, year) %>%
  summarise(total_pills=sum(dosage_unit, na.rm = TRUE),
            total_population=sum(population, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(pills_per_person=total_pills/total_population)

# Step 5: Join your pills per person table to a county level shapefile

geo_pills_population_county_wv <- county_geodata %>%
  inner_join(pills_population_county_wv, by=c("GEOID" = "countyfips"))

# Step 6: Draw the facet map

geo_pills_population_county_wv %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = pills_per_person)) +
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow=2) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='Pills per Person',title="Pill shipments spiked in southern WV in 2008, before fading", subtitle = "Pills per person shipped to West Virginia counties, 2006 to 2012", caption = "Source: ARCOS database") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma",labels = comma)

Task: Modify the facet map you just created to show West Virginia AND Kentucky counties, and only show 2006, 2007, 2008 and 2009, instead of all 9 years.

It should look like this: https://github.com/smussenden/spring20-data-journalism/blob/master/in_class_assignments/class_07/images/task2.png

#Filtering pills population table to just have West Virginia and Kentucky. 
pills_population_county_wv_ky <- pills_population %>%
  filter(buyer_state %in% c("WV","KY")) %>%
  filter(year %in% c(2006, 2007,2008,2009)) %>%
  group_by(countyfips, buyer_county, buyer_state, year) %>%
  summarise(total_pills=sum(dosage_unit, na.rm = TRUE),
            total_population=sum(population, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(pills_per_person=total_pills/total_population)

#Join to shapefile 
geo_pills_population_county_wv_ky <- county_geodata %>%
  inner_join(pills_population_county_wv_ky, by=c("GEOID" = "countyfips"))

#Draw final facet map
geo_pills_population_county_wv_ky %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = pills_per_person)) +
  facet_wrap(~year, nrow=2) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='Pills per Person',title="Pill shipments spiked most in Appalachian W.V. and Kentucky", subtitle = "Pills per person shipped to West Virginia, Kentucky counties, 2006 to 2009", caption = "Source: ARCOS database") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma",labels = comma)
